The value <img src="https://cdn.artofproblemsolving.com/attachments/6/f/8370d9b7a3ca3f74c5b525f994dfbda6548d6.png" width="80">varies over time. Specifically, <img src="https://cdn.artofproblemsolving.com/attachments/9/3/b16d9b24a57416f8c008a5a03ed9850dcaa1e5.png" width="80"> increases by <img src="https://cdn.artofproblemsolving.com/attachments/e/3/5eb55277d130cd9e03ce50b14f0e76e6b33ef7.png" width="80"> every time <img src="https://cdn.artofproblemsolving.com/attachments/3/3/175e21f454b14ff06f19ee5349449ac420235a.png" width="80"></think> <answer>After the first six months, Dr. Zaius will have $\$10,200$.  By the end of the second six months, Dr. Zaius will have $\$10,402$.


\begin{align*}
\text{Amount} &= \text{Principal} \cdot \left(1 + \text{rate}\right)^n \\ &= 10000 \cdot \left(1 + .04\right)^2 \\ &= \$ 10,200. \end{align*}(The value in the exponent of $1 + 0.04$ comes from the fact that interest is being compounded twice a year, for a total of two years.)

\begin{align*}
\text{Amount} &= 10000 \cdot \left(\left(1 + .05\right)^2\right) \\ &= \$ 10,402.\end{align*}

